imagine we have some deviation, so ff merge is not possible
we need three way merge!
but we want a linear simple history!
in this situation we use rebasing.
it means we move the base!
we move the point that other branch is start deviating!
we move it at top, by this act we can remove deviation and make a ff merge!


                           MAIN
                            |
                            v
+------+    +------+    +------+          Note: we can not use ff merge here
| C1   |<---| C2   |<---| C3   |                we have deviation now
+------+    +------+    +------+                we need new commit to apply the merge!
                   ^
                   |
                +------+    +------+
                | B1   |<---| B2   |
                +------+    +------+
                               ^
                               |
                             bugfix


                           MAIN
                            |
                            v
+------+    +------+    +------+          Note: we rebase the other branch
| C1   |<---| C2   |<---| C3   |                we move him on a point that remove the deviation!
+------+    +------+    +------+                it allow us make a ff merge! (just move main to B2)
                           ^                    so we can provide linear history.
                           |
                        +------+    +------+
                        | B1'  |<---| B2'  |
                        +------+    +------+
                                       ^
                                       |
                                     bugfix


Note: commits are "immutable" on git!
      it means we can not change them or modifying them.
      by rebasing we need modify B1 and B2 (need changing the pointer)
      in this situation git create some new commit based on B1 and B2
      like B1' and B2' with new pointer (B1 has pointer to C2
                                         B1' has pointer to C3)
      B1 and B2 will be garbage!

Note: rebasing rewrite History!
      it change where we actually create that branch!
      so if we pushed our history, we should not use rebasing, it create BIG mess!
      but if our history is local, we can use rebasing.
      (imagine some one create a commit top of the B2,
       but we removed B2 by rebasing!
       so we destroyed that person link list!)

Note: usually rebasing introduce new conflict
      after rebasing we need some time to resolve them!

